es. Cannabis has long been prized for the strong and durable fiber in its stalks, its edible and oil-rich seeds, and the psychoactive and medicinal compounds produced by its female flowers. The culturally valuable and often irreplaceable goods derived from cannabis deeply influenced the commercial, medical, ritual, and religious practices of cultures throughout the ages, and human desire for these commodities directed the evolution of the plant toward its contemporary varieties. As interest in cannabis grows and public debate over its many uses rises, this book will help us understand why humanity continues to rely on this plant and adapts it to suit our needs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCannabisxEvolution. 0aCannabisxUtilization. 0aCannabis. 0aHuman-plant relationships. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Botany.2bisacsh  aagriculture.  abotanists.  abotany.  acannabis fibers.  acannabis seeds.  acannabis.  acommercial plant.  acontroversy.  acultural history.  adrugs.  aethnobotany.  ahuman interaction.  ahuman societies.  ainterdisciplinary.  alife sciences.  amarijuana.  amedicinal plants.  anonfiction.  aorigins of cannabis.  aplant evolution.  aplant medicine.  aplant sciences.  apot lovers.  apot.  apsychoactive compounds.  apublic debate.  areligious uses.  aretrospective.  aritual uses.  arole of cannabis.1 aMerlin, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027048040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095457140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954571423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954571/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Pres